The '''Saudi Arabia national football team''' ({{langx|ar|مُنْتَخَب السُّعُودِيَّة لِكُرَّةُ الْقَدَم}}) represents [[Saudi Arabia]] in men's international [[Association football|football]]. They are known as ''Al-Suqour Al-Arabiyyah'' (Arabian Falcons) and sometimes ''Al-Suqour Al-Khodhur'' (The Green Falcons), a reference to their traditional colors of green and white, and represent both [[FIFA]] and the [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC).

Considered one of Asia's most successful national teams, Saudi Arabia have won the [[AFC Asian Cup]] three times (1984, 1988 and 1996), reached a joint record six Asian Cup finals and have qualified for the [[FIFA World Cup]] on seven occasions since debuting at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] tournament. Saudi Arabia are the first Asian team to reach the final of a senior FIFA competition at the [[1992 King Fahd Cup]], which would eventually become the [[FIFA Confederations Cup]]. Only [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] and [[Japan national football team|Japan]] managed to repeat this feat in [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup|1997]] and [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup|2001]] respectively, though Australia achieved it when they were a member of the [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]].

At the 1994 FIFA World Cup, under the leadership of [[Jorge Solari]], Saudi Arabia beat both [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] and [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in the group stage before falling to [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] in the round of 16. Thus, they became the second Arab team in history to reach the knockout stage of a FIFA World Cup after Morocco in [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]], and one of the few Asian national football teams (the others being Australia, Japan, [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] and [[North Korea national football team|North Korea]]) to accomplish such a feat to date. During the [[2022 World Cup|2022 FIFA World Cup]], Saudi Arabia caused a large upset when they beat eventual champions [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] 2–1, the first time Argentina lost to an Asian representative at the World Cup. However, Saudi Arabia then lost the following matches against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] to finish last.

In 2027, Saudi Arabia will host the [[2027 AFC Asian Cup|AFC Asian Cup]], the first time that the nation has ever hosted a major international tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Saudi Arabia confirmed as hosts of the AFC Asian Cup 2027 |url=https://www.the-afc.com/en/about_afc/afc_congress/news/saudi_arabia_confirmed_as_hosts_of_the_afc_asian_cup_2027.html |access-date=2023-05-12 |website=the-AFC |language=en |archive-date=21 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230221161820/https://www.the-afc.com/en/about_afc/afc_congress/news/saudi_arabia_confirmed_as_hosts_of_the_afc_asian_cup_2027.html |url-status=live }}</ref> They will also host the [[2034 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=":02">{{Cite news |last=Panja |first=Tariq |date=15 November 2023 |title=Inside Man: How FIFA Guided the World Cup to Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/11/15/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-fifa-world-cup.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231117041337/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/11/15/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-fifa-world-cup.html |archive-date=17 November 2023 |access-date=17 November 2023 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>